		MKPROJ

A VIMSCRIPT CAN BE FOUND AT
	<https://github.com/lilly-tau/vimscripts/tree/main/mkproj>

		USAGE

	mkproj [-c <config file>] [-t <type>] {-D <variable>=<value>}

-c file
	Sets the config file to be executed, if none are provided, defaults to
	"~/.mkproj".
-t type
	Sets the type to begin at.

-D <variable>=<value>
	Set the variable with the identifier <variable> the value <value>.


		CONFIG FORMAT

A config may be considered a set of line delimited commands which each
consists of a set of tokens delimitted by space, tabs or commas.

A token may be either an identifier literal, a string literal, or a variable
substitution.

An identifier literal comprises of any set of characters which is not
interrupted by spaces, tabs, newlines, or commas.

A string literal is a set of characters enclosed in double quotes,
interspersed with the following escape codes:

	'\n'	Newline
	'\t'	Tab
	'\r'	Carriage return
	'\xNN'	ASCII hex NN

A variable substitution is a dollarsign followed by an identifier.

An identifier is any set of alphabetic characters interspersed with
underscore.

		EXPRESSIONS

An expression is a form of argument given to certain instructions, generally
a list beginning with some leading token, which is not included in the
expression and terminated with a closing parenthesis. An example is the SET
command which may, instead of a token value, be followed by an open
parenthesis and a set of expressions. Like so:

	\ x ( eq $a $b, not $x )

Note that for each expression within a parenthetical, the result is written to
the set variable as each expression is in fact a command with an end result.
This makes the following:

	\ x ( eq $a $b )
	\ x ( not $x )

Equivalent to the aforementioned example. Note also that the opening token
(in this case '(') and the closing token (')') must be delimited (either with
spaces, tabs, or commas) as they must be their own token.

There are the following expressions currently implemented:

	EQ

		eq <token> <token>

	Returns "true" if the tokens specified are exactly string equal,
	otherwise returns "".

	NOT

		not <token>

	Returns "true" if the token evaluates to "", otherwise returns "".

	CAT

		cat <token> <token>

	Returns the string result of concatenating the two token results.

		OUTPUT COMMAND

	">".["0" | "1" | "2"].*<token>

Where the number following the initial '>' determines the output file; files
are enumerated in the order STDIN, STDOUT, STDERR with a default of 1/STDOUT.
This output is required to be flushed by the end of the instruction.

EXAMPLE

	> "Hello World!\n"

		INPUT COMMAND

	< <identifier>

Sets the variable of the identifier specified to a line inputted by the user
(the newline character is not included).

EXAMPLE

	> "What is your name? "
	< name
	> "Hello " $name "\n"

		SET COMMAND

	\ <identifier> (<token> | "(" {expr})

Sets the variable of the identifier specified either to the token specified
or as the result variable to be used for the set of expressions specified.

EXAMPLE

	\ x "Hello"
	> $x "\n"
	\ x ( cat $x " World!" )
	> $x "\n"

		LABEL COMMAND

	@.[@].*($00-$39 | $3B-$FF).[":"]

Skips over a line, and if a colon is included, then it may be found using the
GOTO command as a label. If there is a second '@', when it come across
(without a GOTO) then the program shall exit.

EXAMPLE

	> "Hello World!"
	@@	This text shall not error, and the program shall exit before
	@	Reaching the 'Goodbye World!' message.
	> "Goodbye world!"

		GOTO COMMAND

	%.<token>

Goes to the LABEL specified by the token.

EXAMPLE

	@ Prints "a\nc\n"
	> "a\n"
	%c
	> "b\n"
	@c:
	> "c\n"

		GOTO-IF COMMAND

	("?".<identifier> | "?(" *<expr>) "%".<token>

If the command is passed an identifier (no space) then the GOTO-IF shall check
if that variable is empty, if it is not, then the goto command shall be
executed. Otherwise, it shall not.

If the command is passed expressions, then the GOTO-IF executes the
expressions on the variable "_c" and then acts as though it was called as
"?_c".

EXAMPLE

	\ x ( eq $a $b )
	?x %equal
	> "a and b are equal!"
	@equal:

	@@ Which is equivalent to the following

	?( eq $a $b ) %equal
	> "a and b are equal!"
	@equal:
	@@

		MKDIR COMMAND

	~ <token>

Tries to create a directory of the token specified.

		PIPE COMMAND

	"|".*("|" | "&" | "$")

The pipe command shall write a line of text to the file specified in the
"output" variable. If this variable is not an existing file, it is created.
If it is an invalid file/you do not have permission to access it, then the
pipe shall fail.

If the pipe is followed by a second pipe, the write is not appended but
instead overwrites the file. If it is followed by an ampersand, the write
has no newline appended to it. As a result of this, a file may be cleared
using "||&" immediately followed by a newline. If it is followed by a
dollarsign, then the following token shall be interpretted as an identifier
as opposed to the beginning of a line.

Unless a variable is specified with the dollarsign flag, the pipe takes its
input until newline in its entirety, save for a single leading whitespace (if
present) which is removed. This allows for programs written through pipes to
be reasonably seamless to simply writing them normally.

EXAMPLE

	> "What should the message be? "
	< message
	\ output "test.c"
	||&
	|	#include <stdio.h>
	|	#include <stdlib.h>
	|
	|	int
	|	main(int argc, char **argv)
	|	{
	|&		printf("
	|&$ message
	| \n");
	|	}
